[[Image:Korovin cafe.JPG|thumb|Caf<U+00E9> de la Paix in 1906, by [[Konstantin Korovin]].]]
'''Caf<U+00E9> de la Paix''' ({{IPA-fr|kafe d<U+0259> la p<U+025B>}}) is a famous [[caf<U+00E9>]] in the [[9th arrondissement of Paris|9th arrondissement]] of [[Paris]], [[France]].  It was designed by [[Charles Garnier (architect)|Charles Garnier]], the architect of the [[Palais Garnier|Paris Op<U+00E9>ra]] (located across the plaza). Legend has it that if one sits at the caf<U+00E9>, one is bound to run into a friend or acquaintance as the bar is so well-known and popular.

==History==
The Caf<U+00E9> de la Paix opened June 30, 1862, to serve the Grand-H<U+00F4>tel de la Paix (named after the nearby [[rue de la Paix]]), whose name was later shortened to Grand-H<U+00F4>tel.<ref>Jacques Hillairet, ''Dictionnaire historique des rues de Paris'' (Paris: Editions de Minuit, 8th ed., 1985), vol. I, p. 265.</ref> It serviced visitors of [[Expo (exhibition)|Expo exhibition]] in 1867. Its proximity to the [[Palais Garnier]] attracted many famous clients, including [[Jules Massenet]], [[<U+00C9>mile Zola]], and [[Guy de Maupassant]].  The Caf<U+00E9> is also the setting for the poem "The Absinthe Drinker" by the Canadian poet, [[Robert W. Service|Robert Service]] <ref>[http://plagiarist.com/poetry/4142/]</ref>

During the [[Belle <U+00C9>poque]], visitors to the Caf<U+00E9> included [[Sergei Diaghilev]], and the  [[Prince of Wales]] and future King of the [[United Kingdom]], [[Edward VII]].

A radio studio was later installed in the Caf<U+00E9>, which broadcast the program "This is Paris" to the [[United States]].

On August 22, 1975, the Caf<U+00E9> was declared a historic site by the French government.<ref>[http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=REF&VALUE_1=PA00088909 Notice number PA00088909], sur la base M<U+00E9>rim<U+00E9>e, minist<U+00E8>re de la Culture</ref>

